    <div class="site-layout">
      <main class="page article-page">
        <section class="hero">
          <p class="eyebrow">Skill-Building Tools</p>

          <h1>Practical tools for translating experience, building language, and moving with more clarity</h1>

          <p class="lede">
            These tools are designed for people navigating early-career librarianship, career transitions, job searching, rejection, uncertainty, and professional identity work.
          </p>

          <p class="lede">
            They are not meant to turn every professional challenge into an individual self-improvement project. They are meant to help you name what you already know, recognize transferable skills, and build usable language for next steps.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="content-card">
          <p>
            Skill-building does not always mean starting from zero.
          </p>

          <p>
            Many people entering librarianship already bring experience in teaching, customer service, research, organizing information, outreach, technology, supervision, writing, care work, project coordination, or community support.
          </p>

          <p>
            The challenge is often learning how to translate that experience into the language of library work without minimizing where you came from.
          </p>
        </section>

        <section class="use-box">
          <h2>Use These Tools If...</h2>

          <p>
            You are trying to describe your experience, prepare for interviews, revise a resume, process a difficult professional moment, or understand how your previous work connects to librarianship.
          </p>

          <p>
            Start with the tool that matches your current need. You do not need to complete everything.
          </p>
        </section>

        <article class="article-section" id="tools-overview">
          <h2>Choose a Tool</h2>

          <div class="related-grid">
            <a href="reflection-tools.html">
              Reflection Tools
            </a>

            <a href="#professional-skills-translator">
              Professional Skills Translator
            </a>
          </div>

          <p>
            Reflection tools are useful when you need to slow down and make sense of an experience. The skills translator is useful when you need to convert existing work experience into librarian language for resumes, interviews, or professional identity building.
          </p>
        </article>

        <article class="article-section translator-section" id="professional-skills-translator">
          <p class="reflection-label">Interactive Tool</p>

          <h2>Professional Skills Translator</h2>

          <p>
            Use this tool to connect work you have already done to librarian skills, resume language, and interview talking points.
          </p>

          <p>
            This tool does not decide whether you are qualified. It helps you recognize and describe transferable experience in language that fits library work.
          </p>

          <form class="translator-form" id="career-translator-form">
            <fieldset>
              <legend>1. What field are you coming from?</legend>

              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="education" /> Education</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="customer-service" /> Customer service, retail, or hospitality</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="healthcare" /> Healthcare or care work</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="nonprofit" /> Nonprofit or community work</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="business" /> Business or administration</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="technology" /> Information technology</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="research" /> Research or graduate study</label>
              <label><input name="field" type="checkbox" value="arts" /> Arts, museums, archives, or cultural work</label>
            </fieldset>

            <fieldset>
              <legend>2. What kinds of work have you done?</legend>

              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="service" /> Customer service or public-facing work</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="teaching" /> Teaching, training, tutoring, or coaching</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="supervision" /> Supervising staff, students, or volunteers</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="projects" /> Managing projects or workflows</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="research" /> Research or information gathering</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="writing" /> Writing, editing, or communications</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="events" /> Event planning or programming</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="technology" /> Technology support or troubleshooting</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="outreach" /> Outreach or community engagement</label>
              <label><input name="skills" type="checkbox" value="records" /> Records, files, data, or information management</label>
            </fieldset>

            <fieldset>
              <legend>3. Which library setting interests you most?</legend>

              <label><input name="setting" required type="radio" value="academic" /> Academic libraries</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="public" /> Public libraries</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="school" /> School libraries</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="archives" /> Archives or special collections</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="health" /> Health sciences libraries</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="law-government" /> Law or government libraries</label>
              <label><input name="setting" type="radio" value="unsure" /> Unsure</label>
            </fieldset>

            <fieldset>
              <legend>4. Which areas feel less familiar?</legend>

              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="reference" /> Reference and research help</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="instruction" /> Library instruction</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="cataloging" /> Cataloging or metadata</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="collections" /> Collection development</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="archives" /> Archives or preservation</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="assessment" /> Assessment and data</label>
              <label><input name="growth" type="checkbox" value="management" /> Management or leadership</label>
            </fieldset>

            <fieldset>
              <legend>5. Where are you in the MLIS path?</legend>

              <label><input name="mlis" required type="radio" value="student" /> Current MLIS student</label>
              <label><input name="mlis" type="radio" value="yes" /> Already have an MLIS</label>
              <label><input name="mlis" type="radio" value="no" /> Do not have an MLIS</label>
              <label><input name="mlis" type="radio" value="considering" /> Considering an MLIS</label>
            </fieldset>

            <div class="translator-actions">
              <button type="submit">Generate translation</button>
              <button type="button" id="career-translator-reset">Reset</button>
            </div>
          </form>

          <div class="translator-output" id="career-translator-output" aria-live="polite" hidden></div>
